nd -- every change is either a test we can revert or a fix based on something we proved. _newline__newline_Structure Example:_newline_Before each change: State the hypothesis. _quote_Adding these 10 functions to helper.py will not break existing functionality because they are new function definitions that nothing currently calls._quote__newline_Make one change. Not two. Not _quote_while we are in there let us also fix..._quote_ One change._newline_Rebuild. docker compose build --no-cache mettaclaw for any file change._newline_Verify the container still iterates. If iterations stop, the change broke something. Revert and diagnose._newline_Verify the new thing works. If the change was adding functions, test that they are callable._newline_Document what we learned. Update the wiring knowledge._newline_Then next change._newline_On item 3: The first step is the lowest-risk change that gives us the most information._newline_That is 6c: Copy the 6 soul MeTTa files into the repo. Here is why:_newline_These files are pure (= ...) definitions. They do not execute anything. They do not modify any existing file. They just sit in the soul/ directory. If they cause a problem, we delete them. If they do not, we know the file structure is compatible with the repo layout._newline_Hypothesis: Copying 6 new .metta files into /PeTTa/repos/omegaclaw/soul/ will not affect container behavior because nothing imports them yet. The container will iterate normally._newline_How to test: Copy the files, rebuild, check that iterations continue._newline_What we learn: Whether the files survive the build process, whether the paths are correct, and whether any file naming conflicts exist with what is already in soul/. 
