e to flow into (--> test-thread-state improves-goal-generation) through deduction across the three bridge implications, with revision composing the converging evidence and processing the substrate refutation against Path-3._newline__newline_What is the final truth value on (--> test-thread-state improves-goal-generation) after all evidence is processed? Show your work: which deductions you ran, which revisions you composed, in what order, and the intermediate truth values at each step. Then state the final answer._newline__newline_--> Question 2: Next-step coherence given the arbitrated answer._newline_The thread declares a next-step: next-step-run-fourth-derivation-in-convergence-conditions. Given the arbitrated answer from Question 1, is this next-step structurally appropriate? Specifically: does running a fourth derivation address what the arbitration revealed (the convergence is moderate, the divergence has been refuted), or does it pursue a different concern that the arbitration result does not actually need addressed? Reason via your query results, not via narrative._newline__newline_--> Question 3: Substrate refutation effectiveness._newline_The substrate refutation atom ((--> test-thread-path-3 path-conclusion-degrades-goal-generation) (stv 0.0 0.91)) is intended to weaken Path-3_apostrophe_s evidence before it contributes to the shared conclusion through the bridge implication._newline_Show via MeTTa queries: did the refutation atom actually weaken Path-3 in the engine_apostrophe_s processing? At what point in the arbitration did the weakening occur (before bridge deduction, during, after)? What is Path-3_apostrophe_s effective truth value when it contributes to the shared conclusion?_newline__newline_--> Question 4: Order-invariance of the arbitration._newline_You raised this point in your sketch: the order in which revision happens matters. If the engine revises Path-3 against substrate refutation BEFORE deducing through the bridge, Path-3 contribution is